Based on the search results, here are three TypeScript decorator examples:

### 1. Method Decorator

Method decorators are applied to methods within a class. This example creates a `@log` decorator that logs method calls and their return values:

```typescript
// Method Decorator Example
function log(target: any, key: string, descriptor: PropertyDescriptor) {
  const original = descriptor.value;

  descriptor.value = function(...args: any[]) {
    console.log(`Calling ${key} with arguments: ${JSON.stringify(args)}`);
    const result = original.apply(this, args);
    console.log(`Method ${key} returned: ${JSON.stringify(result)}`);
    return result;
  };

  return descriptor;
}

class Calculator {
  @log
  add(a: number, b: number): number {
    return a + b;
  }
}

const calc = new Calculator();
calc.add(1, 2); // Logs details about the method call and return value
```

### 2. Class Decorator

Class decorators are applied to the class itself and can be used to observe, modify, or replace a class definition:

```typescript
// Class Decorator Example
function sealed(constructor: Function) {
  console.log('Class has been sealed.');
  Object.seal(constructor);
  Object.seal(constructor.prototype);
}

@sealed
class BankAccount {
  private balance: number = 0;

  constructor(public name: string) {}

  deposit(amount: number) {
    this.balance += amount;
  }

  getBalance() {
    return this.balance;
  }
}
```

### 3. Property Decorator

Property decorators are applied to class properties and can be used to modify their behavior:

```typescript
// Property Decorator Example
function Format(formatString: string) {
  return function(target: any, key: string) {
    let val = target[key];

    const getter = function() {
      return val;
    };

    const setter = function(next: any) {
      console.log(`Setting ${key} to ${next}`);
      val = next;
    };

    Object.defineProperty(target, key, {
      get: getter,
      set: setter,
      enumerable: true,
      configurable: true
    });
  };
}

class User {
  @Format('Mr. %s')
  name: string;

  constructor(name: string) {
    this.name = name;
  }
}
```

These examples demonstrate the three main types of TypeScript decorators: method decorators, class decorators, and property decorators. Each type serves a different purpose but all follow the decorator pattern of modifying or extending the behavior of the decorated item.

