The Julian Date for October 4, 1582 (the day before the Gregorian calendar reform took effect) is 2299160.5.

This date is historically significant because the following day in the Gregorian calendar was October 15, 1582 - skipping 10 days to correct the accumulated error in the Julian calendar. This was when Pope Gregory XIII's calendar reform was first implemented in Catholic countries, though other regions adopted the change in later years.

The Julian Date (JD) is a continuous count of days since noon on January 1, 4713 BCE (Julian calendar), making it useful for astronomical calculations and for tracking time across different calendar systems.

